# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: object-pascal
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Delphi's compilers generate native code for Microsoft Windows, macOS, iOS, Android and Linux (x64).
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Delphi includes a code editor, a visual designer, an integrated debugger, a source code control component, and support for third-party plugins.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] The code editor features Code Insight (code completion), Error Insight (real-time error-checking), and refactoring.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] The visual forms designer has the option of using either the Visual Component Library (VCL) for pure Windows development or the FireMonkey (FMX) framework for cross-platform development.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Database support is a key feature and is provided by FireDAC (Database Access Components).
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Delphi is known for its fast compilation speed, native code, and developer productivity.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Delphi was originally developed by Borland as a rapid application development tool for Windows as the successor of Turbo Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Delphi added full object-oriented programming to the existing language, and the language has grown to support generics, anonymous methods, closures, and native Component Object Model (COM) support.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Delphi and its C++ counterpart, C++Builder, are interoperable and jointly sold under the name RAD Studio.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] There are Professional, Enterprise, and Architect editions, with the higher editions having more features at a higher price.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] There is also a free-of-charge Community edition, with most of the features of Professional, but restricted to users and companies with low revenue.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Delphi supports rapid application development (RAD).
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Prominent features are a visual designer and two application frameworks, Visual Component Library (VCL) for Windows and FireMonkey (FMX) for cross-platform development.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Delphi uses the Pascal-based programming language Object Pascal created by Anders Hejlsberg for Borland (now IDERA) as the successor to Turbo Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] It supports native cross-compilation to many platforms including Windows, Linux, iOS, and Android.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] To better support development for Microsoft Windows and interoperate with code developed with other software development tools, Delphi supports independent interfaces of Component Object Model (COM) with reference counting class implementations, and support for many third-party components.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Interface implementations can be delegated to fields or properties of classes.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Message handlers are implemented by tagging a method of a class with the integer constant of the message to handle.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Database connectivity is extensively supported through VCL database-aware and database access components.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Later versions have included upgraded and enhanced runtime library routines, some provided by the community group FastCode.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Delphi uses a strongly typed high-level programming language, intended to be easy to use and originally based on the earlier Object Pascal language.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Turbo Pascal and its descendants, including Delphi, support access to hardware and low-level programming, with the facility to incorporate code written in assembly language and other languages.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Delphi's object-orientation features only class- and interface-based polymorphism.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Objects are references to the objects (as in Java), which Delphi implicitly de-references, so there is usually no need to manually allocate memory for pointers to objects or use similar techniques that some other languages need.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] There are dedicated reference-counted string types, and also null-terminated strings.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Strings can be concatenated by using the '+' operator, rather than using functions.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] For dedicated string types, Delphi handles memory management without programmer intervention.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Since Borland Developer Studio 2006, there are functions to locate memory leaks.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] The Delphi products all ship with a run-time library (RTL) and a Visual Component Library (VCL), including most of its source code.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Third-party components (sometimes with full source code) and tools to enhance the IDE or for other Delphi related development tasks are available, some free of charge.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] The IDE includes a GUI for localization and translation of created programs that may be deployed to a translator; there are also third-party tools with more features for this purpose.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] The VCL framework maintains a high level of source compatibility between versions, which simplifies updating existing source code to a newer Delphi version.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Third-party libraries typically need updates from the vendor but, if source code is supplied, recompilation with the newer version may be sufficient.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] The VCL was an early adopter of dependency injection or inversion of control; it uses a reusable component model, extensible by the developer.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] With class helpers, new functionality can be introduced to core RTL and VCL classes without changing the original source code of the RTL or VCL.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Delphi supports a wide range of third-party database access components that provide native connectivity to major database systems.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] These include specialized libraries for Oracle, SQL Server, MySQL/MariaDB, PostgreSQL, SQLite, and InterBase/Firebird.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Some components, like DAC, offer universal data access solutions supporting multiple databases and cloud services such as Salesforce and FreshBooks.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] These libraries are regularly updated to remain compatible with the latest IDE versions (e.g., RAD Studio 12), operating systems (e.g., macOS Sonoma, iOS 17, Android 13), and database engines (e.g., Oracle 23, SQL Server 2022, PostgreSQL 16).
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] The compiler is optimizing and is a single-pass compiler.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] It can optionally compile to a single executable which does not require DLLs.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Delphi can also generate standard DLLs, ActiveX DLLs, COM automation servers and Windows services.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] The Delphi IDEs since Delphi 2005 increasingly support refactoring features such as method extraction and the possibility to create UML models from the source code or to modify the source through changes made in the model.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Delphi has communities on the web, where also its employees actively participate.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] And Delphi is using in collaboration with FireDAC components.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Delphi is one of the languages where backward compatibility is close to 100%.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Although each new release of Delphi attempts to keep as much backward compatibility as possible to allow existing code reuse, new features, new libraries, and improvements sometimes make newer releases less than 100% backward compatible.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Since 2016, there have been new releases of Delphi every six months, with new platforms being added approximately every second release.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Delphi and its C++ counterpart, C++Builder, are interoperable.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] They share many core components, notably the IDE, the VCL and FMX frameworks, and much of the runtime library.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] In addition, they can be used jointly in a project.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] For example, C++Builder 6 and later can combine source code from Delphi and C++ in one project, while packages compiled with C++Builder can be used from within Delphi.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] In 2007, the products were released jointly as RAD Studio, a shared host for Delphi and C++Builder, which can be purchased with either or both.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Starting with Rio, there is also interoperability with Python.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Note that the object construct is still available in Delphi.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] In 2016, Delphi was named the language of choice for teaching programming in South African schools as a subject of information technology (IT).
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Embarcadero used to publish "roadmaps" describing their future development plans.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] The last one was published in November 2020.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Version 10.5 referred to in the November 2020 roadmap was renamed 11.0.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Starting with Delphi 11, Embarcadero decided to no longer publish formal roadmaps.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] Instead, possible new features are now presented in a loose order through blog entries and online webinars.
[src:object-pascal/delphi-software] An important role has Marco Cantú (product manager) with his blog.
[src:object-pascal/docs] you must have javascript and style sheets enabled in order to view the html documentation correctly.
[src:object-pascal/docs] You can also download the documentation in some alternative formats.
[src:object-pascal/docs] The above is the documentation of the latest released version of Free Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/docs] The documentation is also generated daily based on the current status of the source repositories.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] It supports its own Object Pascal dialect, as well as the dialects of several other Pascal family compilers to a certain extent, including those of Borland Pascal (named "Turbo Pascal" until the 1990 version 6), Borland (later Embarcadero) Delphi, and some historical Macintosh compilers.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The dialect is selected on a per-unit (module) basis, and more than one dialect can be used per program.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] It follows a *write once, compile anywhere* philosophy and is available for many CPU architectures and operating systems (see Targets).
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] It supports inline assembly language and includes an internal assembler capable of parsing several dialects such as AT&T and Intel style.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] There are separate projects to facilitate developing cross-platform graphical user interface (GUI) applications, the most prominent one being the Lazarus integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Initially, Free Pascal adopted the *de facto* standard dialect of Pascal programmers, Borland Pascal, but later adopted Delphi's Object Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] From version 2.0 on, Delphi compatibility has been continuously implemented or improved.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] A small effort has been made to support some of the Apple Pascal syntax to ease interfacing to the Classic Mac OS and macOS.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The Apple dialect implements some standard Pascal features that Turbo Pascal and Delphi omit.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The 2.2.*x* release series did not significantly change the dialect objectives beyond roughly Delphi 7 level syntax, instead aiming for closer compatibility.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] A notable exception to this was the addition of support for generics to Free Pascal in version 2.2.0, several years before they were supported in any capacity by Delphi.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] In 2011 several Delphi 2006-specific features were added in the development branch, and some of the starting work for the features new in Delphi 2009 (most notably the addition of the `UnicodeString` type) was completed.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The development branch also has an *Objective-Pascal* extension for Objective-C (Cocoa) interfacing.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Beginning with version 2.7.1, Free Pascal added support for ISO Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] As of version 3.0.0, it has been able to compile standardpascal.org's P5 ISO Pascal compiler with no changes.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Free Pascal was created when Borland clarified that Borland Pascal development for MS-DOS would stop with version 7.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Student Florian Paul Klämpfl began developing his own compiler written in the Turbo Pascal dialect which produced 32-bit code for the GO32v1 DOS extender, (developed and used by the DJ's GNU Programming Platform project).
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Originally, the compiler was a 16-bit executable compiled by Turbo Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] After two years, the compiler was able to compile itself into a 32-bit executable.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The initial 32-bit compiler was published on the Internet, and the first contributors joined the project.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Later, a Linux port was created by Michael van Canneyt, five years before the Borland Kylix Pascal compiler for Linux became available.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The DOS port was adapted for use in OS/2 using the Eberhard Mattes eXtender (EMX) which made OS/2 the second supported compiling target.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] As well as Florian Klämpfl the original author, Daniël Mantione also contributed significantly to make this happen, providing the original port of the run-time library to OS/2 and EMX.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The compiler improved gradually, and the DOS version migrated to the GO32v2 extender.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] This culminated in release 0.99.5, which was much more widely used than prior versions, and was the last release aiming only for Borland Pascal compliance; later releases added a Delphi compatibility mode.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] This release was also ported to systems using Motorola 68000 family (m68k) processors.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] With release 0.99.8 the Win32 target was added, and a start was made with incorporating some Delphi features.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Stabilizing for a non-beta release began, and version 1.0 was released in July 2000.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The 1.0.*x* series was widely used, in business and education.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] For the 1.0.*x* releases, the port to 68k CPU was redone, and the compiler produced stable code for several 68k Unix-like and AmigaOS operating systems.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] During the stabilization of what would become 1.0.*x*, and also when porting to the Motorola 68k systems, it was clear that the design of the code generator was far too limited in many aspects.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The principal problems were that adding processors meant rewriting the code generator, and that the register allocation was based on the principle of always keeping three free registers between building blocks, which was inflexible and difficult to maintain.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] For these reasons, the 1.1.*x* series branched off from the 1.0.*x* main branch in December 1999.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] At first, changes were mostly clean-ups and rewrite-redesigns to all parts of the compiler.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The code generator and register allocator were also rewritten.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Any remaining missing Delphi compatibility was added.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The work on 1.1.x continued slowly but steadily.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] In late 2003, a working PowerPC port became available, followed by an ARM port in summer 2004, a SPARC port in fall 2004, and an x86-64-AMD64 port in early 2004, which made the compiler available for a 64-bit platform.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] In November 2003, a first beta release of the 1.1.*x* branch was packaged and numbered 1.9.0.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] These were quickly followed by versions 1.9.2 and 1.9.4; the latter introduced OS X support.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] In 2006, some of the major reworks planned for 2.2, such as the rewrite of the unit system, had still not begun, and it was decided to instead start stabilizing the already implemented features.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Some of the motives for this roadmap change were the needs of the Lazarus integrated development environment project, particularly the internal linker, support for Win64, Windows CE, and OS X on x86, and related features like DWARF.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] After betas 2.1.2 and 2.1.4, version 2.2.0 was released in September 2007, followed by version 2.2.2 in August 2008 and version 2.2.4 in March 2009.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The 2.2.*x* series vastly improved support for the ActiveX and Component Object Model (COM) interface, and Object Linking and Embedding (OLE), though bugs were still being found.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The delegation to interface using the `implements` keyword was partly implemented, but was not complete as of March 2011.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Library support for ActiveX was also improved.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Another major feature was the internal linker for Win32, Win64, and Windows CE, which greatly improved linking time and memory use, and make the compile-link-run cycle in Lazarus much faster.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The efficiency for smart-linking, or dead code elimination, was also improved.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Minor new features included improved DWARF (2/3) debug format support, and optimizations such as tail recursion, omission of unneeded stack frames and register-based common subexpression elimination (CSE) optimization.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] A first implementation of generic programming (generics) support also became available, but only experimentally.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The 2.4.x release series had a less clear set of goals than earlier releases.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The unit system rewrite was postponed again, and the branch that became 2.4 was created to keep risky commits from 2.2 to stabilize it.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Mostly these risky commits were more involved improvements to the new platforms, Mac PowerPC 64, Mac x86-64, iPhone, and many fixes to the ARM and x86-64 architectures in general, as well as DWARF.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Other compiler improvements included whole program optimization (WPO) and devirtualization and ARM embedded-application binary interface (EABI) support.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Later, during the 2.2 cycle, a more Delphi-like resource support (based on special sections in the binary instead of Pascal constants) was added.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] This feature, direly needed by Lazarus, became the main highlight of the branch.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Other more minor additions were a memory manager that improved heap manager performance in threaded environments, small improvements in Delphi compatibility such as `OleVariant`, and improvements in interface delegation.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] On January 1, 2010, Free Pascal 2.4.0 was released, followed on November 13, 2010, by bug fix release 2.4.2, with support for `for..in` loops, `sealed` and `abstract` classes, and other changes.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] In January 2012, Free Pascal 2.6 was released.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] This first version from the 2.6 release series also supported Objective Pascal on OS X and iOS targets and implemented many small improvements and bug fixes.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] In February 2013, FPC 2.6.2 was released.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] It contained NetBSD and OpenBSD releases for the first time since 1.0.10, based on fresh ports.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] In March 2014, the last point release in the 2.6 series, 2.6.4, was launched, featuring mostly database (fcl-db) updates.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Version 3.0.0 was released on November 25, 2015, and was the first major release since January 1, 2012.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] It introduced many new language features.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Version 3.0.2 was released on February 15, 2017, and includes bug fixes and minor compiler updates.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Version 3.0.4 was released on November 28, 2017.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] It includes many language improvements over previous versions, including an internal linker for Executable and Linkable Format (ELF), Arm AARCH64 for iOS and Linux, a revived i8086 platform, extended libraries and much more.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The next major release, version 3.2.0, was published on June 19, 2020.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] It introduced many new language features, including generic routines, standard namespaces, managed records and expanded functionality for dynamic arrays, in addition to the advent of new standard units and the support of additional platforms.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Version 3.2.2 was released on May 20, 2021, and supports macOS on AArch64 and naming of threads.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Additionally it includes bug fixes and minor compiler updates.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] A release candidate, FPC 3.2.4-rc1, was available for test in June 2025.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] As of July 2025 development version 3.3.1 was available for download as file `fpc.zip`.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The most recent member of the archive (excepting a file stating the date the members of `ftp.zip` were extracted) was dated 15 September 2023.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Free Pascal also supports byte code generation for the Java Virtual Machine as of version 3.0.0 and targets both Oracle's Java and Google's Android JVM, although Object Pascal syntax is not fully supported.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Free Pascal 3.0.0 also supports ARMHF platforms like the Raspberry Pi, including ARMV6-EABIHF running on Raspbian.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Work on 64-bit ARM has resulted in support for iOS in 3.0.0 as well.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] A native ARM Android target has been added, ending the formerly hacked ARM Linux target to generate native ARM libraries for Android.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] This makes porting Lazarus applications to Android (using Custom Drawn Interface) easier.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Since FPC 2.6.2, OpenBSD and NetBSD are supported on IA32 and X86_64 architectures.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] A new target *embedded* has been added for usage without OS (ARM Cortex M and MIPS mainly).
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] With InstantFPC it is possible to run Pascal programs, which are translated just in time, as Unix scripts or CGI back-end.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Ultibo core is an embedded or bare metal development environment for Raspberry Pi.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Ultibo is based on Free Pascal and developed under a modified version of Lazarus.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The IDE is PC based but has been ported to Linux and Mac as well.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Ultibo is an OS-less runtime and has support for most functions and allows the programmer full control over the hardware via the RTL units.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The runtime implements multi-threaded, pre-emptive multitasking.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] The programmer can put threads on a specific CPU or let the runtime divide the load automatically or a mix of the two.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Most Raspberry Pi models are supported including the A, B, A+ and B+ as well as the Raspberry Pi 2B, 3B, 4B/400/CM4 and Zero.
[src:object-pascal/free-pascal] Like most modern compilers, Free Pascal can be used with an integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Lazarus is often used to create native-code console and graphical user interface (GUI) applications for desktop computers, mobile devices, web applications, web services, visual components, and function libraries for several different operating system platforms, including macOS, Linux, and Windows.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] A project created by using Lazarus on one platform can be compiled on any other one which Free Pascal compiler supports.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] For desktop applications, one source code can target macOS, Linux, and Windows, with little or no modification.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] For example, the Lazarus IDE is created from one code base and available on all major platforms including Raspberry Pi.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Lazarus was started in February 1999 by three developers, Cliff Baeseman, Shane Miller, and Michael A.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Hess, who had previously attempted to contribute to the Megido project, an earlier open source effort to build a Delphi like IDE for Free Pascal that dissolved due to internal disagreements and architectural issues.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] In frustration, they founded Lazarus as an independent project to accomplish the same goal.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] The project was hosted on SourceForge and attracted community contributors through mailing lists and version control systems.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Marc Weustink joined in August 1999 and made foundational contributions to the debugger and core components.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Mattias Gaertner joined in September 2000 and has been one of the principal contributors to the IDE's core since then.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] The original founders are no longer involved with the project.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Lazarus provides a *What You See Is What You Get* (WYSIWYG) development environment for creating rich user interfaces, application logic, and other supporting code artifacts, similar to Delphi.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Lazarus uses Free Pascal as its back-end compiler.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] As Free Pascal supports cross-compiling, Lazarus applications can be cross-compiled from Windows, Linux, or macOS to any of the supported Free Pascal compilation targets.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Applications for embedded devices (smartphones, PDAs, routers, game consoles) can be cross-compiled from any desktop platform.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Lazarus provides a cross-platform application framework called the Lazarus Component Library (LCL), which provides a single, unified interface for programmers, with different platform-specific implementations.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Using LCL, it is possible to create applications in a *write once, compile anywhere* manner, unless system-dependent features are used explicitly.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] LCL was originally modeled after the Visual Component Library (VCL) in Delphi 6, but is not restricted to Windows.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] This is done by separating the definition of common widget classes and their widgetset-specific implementation.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Each widget set is supported by providing an *interface* which interacts directly with the set.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Developers can install packages that allow Lazarus to support several database management systems (DBMSes).
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Programs can interact with a DBMS through code or by components dropped on a form.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] It supports Component Object Model (COM) since version 2.2.0, and offers most of Delphi's networking functions.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] However, there are limits to the performance and feature set.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] This makes the extensive repository of available VCL widgets inaccessible without conversion.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] The conversion effort mostly involves some editing, although there are a few fundamental differences.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] When porting, missing units in the libraries are a considerably bigger problem than incompatibilities between LCL and VCL.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Components for Delphi can be converted to work in Lazarus.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] This can be complex, though less so than for Lazarus versions older than 0.9.30, based on FP 2.4.x.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] On Windows, the default size of an executable file is larger than the Delphi 6 or 7 equivalent, as Lazarus stores debug information within the executable, rather than as separate files.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Starting with version 0.9.30, Lazarus supports external debug symbols via compiler options.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Thus, program file sizes can be significantly reduced.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Alternatively, debug info can be stripped from EXEs (e.g. using a port of the UNIX `strip` command).
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Like Free Pascal, Lazarus is free software.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Different portions are distributed under different free software licenses, including GPL, LGPL, MPL, and a modified version of LGPL.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] LCL, which is statically built into the produced executables, is licensed under a modified version of the LGPL, granting extra permissions to allow it to be statically built into the produced software, including proprietary ones.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Installing a design time package is equivalent to linking to the IDE, so that distributing the Lazarus IDE with a GPL-incompatible design-time package such as the JEDI packages licensed under the Mozilla Public License, pre-installed would cause a license violation.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] This does not prohibit proprietary packages from being developed with Lazarus.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] The first attempt to develop an IDE for Free Pascal dates back to 1998, under the "Megido" project.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] After the project failed, some of its developers started a new project based on a more flexible foundation.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] The name "Lazarus" alludes to the revival of the Megido concept.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] It is inspired by Lazarus of Bethany, who, according to the Gospel of John, was restored to life by Jesus four days after his death.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] The first preliminary LCL version was ready for release in 2001.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] In 2003, the first beta version of Lazarus (0.9.0.3) was hosted at SourceForge.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] Lazarus version 1.0 was released in 2012.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] A significantly enhanced Lazarus 1.2 with was released in 2014.
[src:object-pascal/lazarus-ide] More than four million downloads had been made from SourceForge as of March 2014.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] The language was originally developed by Apple Computer as *Clascal* for the Lisa Workshop development system.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] As Lisa gave way to Macintosh, Apple collaborated with Niklaus Wirth, the author of Pascal, to develop an officially standardized version of Clascal.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Through the mid-1980s, Object Pascal was the main programming language for early versions of the MacApp application framework.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] The language lost its place as the main development language on the Mac in 1991 with the release of the C++-based MacApp 3.0.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Symantec also developed a compiler for Object Pascal for their Think Pascal product, which could compile programs much faster than Apple's own Macintosh Programmer's Workshop (MPW).
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Symantec then developed the Think Class Library (TCL), based on MacApp concepts, which could be called from both Object Pascal and THINK C.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] The Think suite largely displaced MPW as the main development platform on the Mac in the late 1980s.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Symantec ported Object Pascal to the PC, and developed a similar object framework on that platform.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] In contrast to TCL, which eventually migrated to C++, the PC libraries remained mainly based on Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Borland added support for object-oriented programming to Turbo Pascal 5.5, which would eventually become the basis for the Object Pascal dialect used in Delphi created by Anders Hejlsberg.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Delphi remained mainstream for business applications on the PC into the early 2000s, and was partly displaced in the 2000s with the introduction of the .NET Framework which included Hejlsberg's C#.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Pascal became a major language in the programming world in the 1970s, with high-quality implementations on most minicomputer platforms and microcomputers.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Among the latter was the UCSD Pascal system, which compiled to an intermediate *p-System* code format that could then run on multiple platforms.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Apple licensed UCSD and used it as the basis for their Apple Pascal system for the Apple II and Apple III.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Pascal became one of the major languages in the company in this period.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] With the start of the Apple Lisa project, Pascal was selected as the main programming language of the platform, although this time as a *compiler* in contrast to the p-System *interpreter*.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Object Pascal is an extension of the Pascal language that was developed at Apple Computer by a team led by Larry Tesler in consultation with Niklaus Wirth, the inventor of Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] It is descended from an earlier object-oriented version of Pascal named Clascal, which was available on the Lisa computer.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Object Pascal was needed to support MacApp, an expandable Macintosh application framework that would now be termed a class library.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Object Pascal extensions, and MacApp, were developed by Barry Haynes, Ken Doyle, and Larry Rosenstein, and were tested by Dan Allen.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Larry Tesler oversaw the project, which began very early in 1985 and became a product in 1986.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] An Object Pascal extension was also implemented in the Think Pascal integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] The IDE includes the compiler and an editor with syntax highlighting and checking, a powerful debugger, and a class library.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Many developers preferred Think Pascal over Apple's implementation of Object Pascal because Think Pascal offered a much faster compile–link–debug cycle, and tight integration of its tools.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] The last official release of Think Pascal was 4.01, in 1992.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Symantec later released an unofficial version 4.5d4 at no charge.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Apple dropped support for Object Pascal when they moved from Motorola 68000 series chips to IBM's PowerPC architecture in 1994.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] MacApp 3.0, had already been rewritten in C++ and ported to this platform.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Metrowerks bundled an Object Pascal compiler with CodeWarrior that targeted both 68k and PowerPC, both in their IDE and as MPW tools.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Macintosh developers using Object Pascal had a path to port to the PowerPC, even after both Apple and Symantec dropped support.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] MacApp 2.0, written in Object Pascal, was ported to the PowerPC using CodeWarrior.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] In 1986, Borland introduced similar extensions, also named Object Pascal, to the Turbo Pascal product for the Macintosh, and in 1989 for Turbo Pascal 5.5 for DOS.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] When Borland refocused from DOS to Windows in 1994, they created a successor to Turbo Pascal, named Delphi, and introduced a new set of extensions to create what is now known as the Delphi language.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] The development of Delphi started in 1993 and Delphi 1.0 was officially released in the United States on 14 February 1995.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] These were inspired by the ISO working draft for object-oriented extensions, but many of the differences from Turbo Pascal's dialect (such as the draft's requirement that all methods be virtual) were ignored.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] The Delphi language has continued to evolve over the years to support constructs such as dynamic arrays, generics and anonymous methods.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] The old object syntax introduced by Apple ("Old-Style Object Types") is still supported.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Object Pascal compilers are available for a wide range of operating systems and architectures.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Pascal Script (formerly *InnerFuse*) and DWScript (Delphi Web Script) are open-source Object Pascal interpreters and scripting engines written in Delphi.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] DWScript can also compile Object Pascal code into JavaScript code (Smart Pascal), and supports just-in-time compilation (JIT).
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Modern Pascal provides 3 different interpreters: a command-line interface (CLI), Apache Module (Celerity), and CodeRunner (node.js like solution able to handle different scripts per port), besides the ability to compile and protect a script's source code.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Here are several "Hello World" programs in different Object Pascal versions.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Still supported in Delphi and Free Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] FPC also packages its own substitutes for the libraries/units.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] The Free Pascal 1.0 series and the FPC textmode IDE are the largest open codebases in this dialect.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Free Pascal 2.0 was rewritten in a more Delphi-like dialect, and the textmode IDE and related frameworks (Free Vision) are the only parts in the TP version of Object Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] This works based on pointer copy, unless there is a specific allocation for a deeper copy.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Note that the object construct is still available in Delphi and Free Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] The method implementation can also be made in a distinct location as in other Object Pascal dialects.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Many features have been introduced continuously to Object Pascal with extensions to Delphi and extensions to FreePascal.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] In reaction to criticism, Free Pascal has adopted generics with the same syntax as Delphi, provided Delphi compatibility mode is selected, and both Delphi (partial) and Free Pascal (more extensive) support operator overloading.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Delphi has also introduced many other features since version 7, including generics.
[src:object-pascal/object-pascal] Whereas FreePascal tries to be compatible to Delphi in Delphi compatibility mode, it also usually introduced many new features to the language that are not always available in Delphi.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal was developed on the pattern of the ALGOL 60 language.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Wirth was involved in the process to improve the language as part of the ALGOL X efforts and proposed a version named ALGOL W.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This was not accepted, and the ALGOL X process bogged down.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] In 1968, Wirth decided to abandon the ALGOL X process and further improve ALGOL W, releasing this as Pascal in 1970.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] On top of ALGOL's scalars and arrays, Pascal enables defining complex data types and building dynamic and recursive data structures such as lists, trees and graphs.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal has strong typing on all objects, which means that one type of data cannot be converted to or interpreted as another without explicit conversions.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Unlike C (and also unlike most other languages in the C family), Pascal allows nested procedure definitions to any depth, and allows most kinds of definitions and declarations inside subroutines (procedures and functions).
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] A program is thus syntactically similar to a single procedure or function.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This is similar to the block structure of ALGOL 60, but restricted from arbitrary block statements to just procedures and functions.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal became very successful in the 1970s, notably on the burgeoning minicomputer market.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Compilers were also available for many microcomputers as the field emerged in the late 1970s.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It was widely used as a teaching language in university-level programming courses in the 1980s, and also used in production settings for writing commercial software during the same period.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It was displaced by the C programming language during the late 1980s and early 1990s as UNIX-based systems became popular, and especially with the release of C++.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] A derivative named Object Pascal designed for object-oriented programming was developed in 1985.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This was used by Apple Computer (for the Lisa and Macintosh machines) and Borland in the late 1980s and later developed into Delphi on the Microsoft Windows platform.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Extensions to the Pascal concepts led to the languages Modula-2 and Oberon, both developed by Wirth.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Much of the history of computer language design during the 1960s can be traced to the ALGOL 60 language.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] ALGOL was developed during the 1950s with the explicit goal of being able to clearly describe algorithms.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It included a number of features for structured programming that remain common in languages to this day.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Shortly after its introduction, in 1962, Wirth began working on his dissertation with Helmut Weber on the Euler programming language.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Euler was based on ALGOL's syntax and many concepts but was not a derivative.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Its primary goal was to add dynamic lists and types, allowing it to be used in roles similar to Lisp.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] By this time, a number of problems in ALGOL had been identified, notably the lack of a standardized string system.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The group tasked with maintaining the language had begun the ALGOL X process to identify improvements, calling for submissions.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Wirth and Tony Hoare submitted a conservative set of modifications to add strings and clean up some of the syntax.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] These were considered too minor to be worth using as the new standard ALGOL, so Wirth wrote a compiler for the language, which became named ALGOL W.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The ALGOL X efforts would go on to choose a much more complex language, ALGOL 68.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The complexity of this language led to considerable difficulty producing high-performance compilers, and it was not widely used in the industry.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This left an opening for newer languages.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal was influenced by the ALGOL W efforts, with the explicit goals of teaching programming in a structured fashion and for the development of system software.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] A generation of students used Pascal as an introductory language in undergraduate courses.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Other goals included providing a reliable and efficient tool for writing large programs, and bridging the canyon between scientific and commercial programming, as represented by the then-widespread languages Fortran and COBOL, with a general-purpose language.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] One of the early successes for the language was the introduction of University of California, San Diego's (UCSD) UCSD Pascal, a version that ran on a custom operating system that could be ported to different platforms.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] A key platform was the Apple II, where it saw widespread use as Apple Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This led to Pascal becoming the primary high-level language used for development in the Apple Lisa, and later, the Macintosh.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Parts of the original Macintosh operating system were hand-translated into Motorola 68000 assembly language from the Pascal source code.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The typesetting system TeX by Donald Knuth was written in WEB, the original literate programming system, based on Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-10 Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Successful commercial applications like Adobe Photoshop were written in Macintosh Programmer's Workshop Pascal, while applications like Total Commander, Skype and Macromedia Captivate were written in Delphi (Object Pascal).
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Apollo Computer used Pascal as the systems programming language for its operating systems beginning in 1980.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Variants of Pascal have also been used for everything from research projects to PC games and embedded systems.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Newer Pascal compilers exist which are widely used.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Wirth's example compiler meant to propagate the language, the Pascal-P system, used a subset of the language designed to be the minimal subset of the language that could compile itself.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The idea was that this could allow bootstrapping the compiler, which would then be extended to full Pascal language status.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This was done with several compilers, but one notable exception was UCSD Pascal, which was based on Pascal-P2.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It kept the subset status of the language based on the idea that this would run better on the new (then) microprocessors with limited memory.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] UCSD also converted the Pascal-P2 interpreter into a "byte machine", again, because it would be a better fit for byte-oriented microprocessors.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] UCSD Pascal formed the basis of many systems, including Apple Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Borland Pascal was not based on the UCSD codebase, but arrived during the popular period of UCSD and matched many of its features.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This started the line that ended with Delphi Pascal and the compatible Open Source compiler FPC/Lazarus.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The ISO standard for Pascal, ISO 7185, was published in 1983 and was widely implemented and used on mainframes, minicomputers and IBM-PCs and compatibles from 16 bits to 32 bits.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The two dialects of Pascal most in use towards the end of the 20th century and up until today are the ISO 7185 standard version and the Delphi/Turbo Pascal versions (of which the two Borland versions are mostly compatible with each other).
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] During work on the Lisa, Larry Tesler began corresponding with Wirth on the idea of adding object-oriented extensions to the language, to make Pascal a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This led initially to Clascal, introduced in 1983.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] As the Lisa program faded and was replaced by the Macintosh, a further version was created and named Object Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This was introduced on the Mac in 1985 as part of the MacApp application framework, and became Apple's main development language into the early 1990s.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The Object Pascal extensions were added to Turbo Pascal with the release of version 5.5 in 1989.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Over the years, Object Pascal became the basis of the Delphi system for Microsoft Windows, which is still used for developing Windows applications, and can cross-compile code to other systems.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Free Pascal is an open source, cross-platform alternative with its own graphical integrated development environment (IDE) named Lazarus.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The first Pascal compiler was designed in Zürich for the CDC 6000 series mainframe computer family.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Niklaus Wirth reports that a first attempt to implement it in FORTRAN 66 in 1969 was unsuccessful due to FORTRAN 66's inadequacy to express complex data structures.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The second attempt was implemented in a C-like language (Scallop by Max Engeli) and then translated by hand (by R.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Schild) to Pascal itself for boot-strapping.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Many Pascal compilers since have been similarly self-hosting, that is, the compiler is itself written in Pascal, and the compiler is usually capable of recompiling itself when new features are added to the language, or when the compiler is to be ported to a new environment.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The GNU Pascal compiler is one notable exception, being written in C.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The first successful port of the CDC Pascal compiler to another mainframe was completed by Welsh and Quinn at the Queen's University of Belfast (QUB) in 1972.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The target was the International Computers Limited (ICL) 1900 series.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This compiler, in turn, was the parent of the Pascal compiler for the Information Computer Systems (ICS) Multum minicomputer.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The Multum port was developed – with a view to using Pascal as a systems programming language – by Findlay, Cupples, Cavouras and Davis, working at the Department of Computing Science in Glasgow University.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It is thought that Multum Pascal, which was completed in the summer of 1973, may have been the first 16-bit implementation.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] A completely new compiler was completed by Welsh et al. at QUB in 1977.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It offered a source-language diagnostic feature (incorporating profiling, tracing and type-aware formatted postmortem dumps) that was implemented by Findlay and Watt at Glasgow University.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This implementation was ported in 1980 to the ICL 2900 series by a team based at Southampton University and Glasgow University.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The Standard Pascal Model Implementation was also based on this compiler, having been adapted, by Welsh and Hay at Manchester University in 1984, to check rigorously for conformity to the BSI 6192/ISO 7185 Standard and to generate code for a portable abstract machine.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The first Pascal compiler written in North America was constructed at the University of Illinois under Donald B.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Gillies for the PDP-11 and generated native machine code.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Microsoft had Pascal compilers for IBM PCs; see Microsoft Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The P-system compilers were named Pascal-P1, Pascal-P2, Pascal-P3, and Pascal-P4.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal-P1 was the first version, and Pascal-P4 was the last to come from Zürich.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The version termed Pascal-P1 was coined after the fact for the many different sources for Pascal-P that existed.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The compiler was redesigned to enhance portability, and issued as Pascal-P2.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This code was later enhanced to become Pascal-P3, with an intermediate code backward compatible with Pascal-P2, and Pascal-P4, which was not backward compatible.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The Pascal-P4 compiler–interpreter can still be run and compiled on systems compatible with original Pascal (as can Pascal-P2).
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] However, it only accepts a subset of the Pascal language.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal-P5, created outside the Zürich group, accepts the full Pascal language and includes ISO 7185 compatibility.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal-P6 is a follow-on to Pascal-P5 that, along with other features, aims to be a compiler for specific CPUs, including AMD64.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] UCSD Pascal branched off Pascal-P2, where Kenneth Bowles used it to create the interpretive UCSD p-System.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It was one of three operating systems available at the launch of the original IBM Personal Computer.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] UCSD Pascal used an intermediate code based on byte values, and thus was one of the earliest *bytecode compilers*.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Apple Pascal was released in 1979 for the Apple II and Apple III computer systems.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It was an implementation of, or largely based on, UCSD Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal-P1 through Pascal-P4 were not, but rather based on the CDC 6600 60-bit word length.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] A compiler based on the Pascal-P4 compiler, which created native binary object files, was released for the IBM System/370 mainframe computer by the Australian Atomic Energy Commission; it was named the *AAEC Pascal 8000 Compiler* after the abbreviation of the name of the commission.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Apple Computer created its own Lisa Pascal for the Lisa Workshop in 1982, and ported the compiler to the Apple Macintosh and MPW in 1985.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] In 1985 Larry Tesler, in consultation with Niklaus Wirth, defined Object Pascal and these extensions were incorporated in both the Lisa Pascal and Mac Pascal compilers.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] In the 1980s, Anders Hejlsberg wrote the Blue Label Pascal compiler for the Nascom-2.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] A reimplementation of this compiler for the IBM PC was marketed under the names Compas Pascal and PolyPascal before it was acquired by Borland and renamed *Turbo Pascal*.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Turbo Pascal became hugely popular, thanks to an aggressive pricing strategy, having one of the first full-screen IDEs, and very fast turnaround time (just seconds to compile, link, and run).
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It was written and highly optimized entirely in assembly language, making it smaller and faster than much of the competition.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] In 1986, Anders ported Turbo Pascal to the Macintosh and incorporated Apple's Object Pascal extensions into Turbo Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] These extensions were then added back into the PC version of Turbo Pascal for version 5.5.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] At the same time Microsoft also implemented the Object Pascal compiler.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Turbo Pascal 5.5 had a large influence on the Pascal community, which began concentrating mainly on the IBM PC in the late 1980s.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Many PC hobbyists in search of a structured replacement for BASIC used this product.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It also began to be adopted by professional developers.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Around the same time a number of concepts were imported from C to let Pascal programmers use the C-based application programming interface (API) of Microsoft Windows directly.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] These extensions included null-terminated strings, pointer arithmetic, function pointers, an address-of operator, and unsafe typecasts.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Turbo Pascal and other derivatives with *unit* or *module* structures are modular programming languages.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] However, it does not provide a nested module concept or qualified import and export of specific symbols.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Super Pascal adds non-numeric labels, a return statement and expressions as names of types.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] TMT Pascal was the first Borland-compatible compiler for 32-bit MS-DOS compatible protected mode, OS/2, and Win32.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It extends the language with function and operator overloading.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The universities of Wisconsin–Madison, Zürich, Karlsruhe, and Wuppertal developed the *Pascal-SC* and *Pascal-XSC* (*Extensions for Scientific Computation*) compilers, aimed at programming numerical computations.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Development for Pascal-SC started in 1978 supporting ISO 7185 Pascal level 0, but level 2 support was added at a later stage.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal-SC originally targeted the Z80 processor, but was later rewritten for DOS (x86) and 68000.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal-XSC has at various times been ported to Unix (Linux, SunOS, HP-UX, AIX) and Microsoft/IBM (DOS with EMX, OS/2, Windows) operating systems.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It operates by generating intermediate C source code which is then compiled to a native executable.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Some of the Pascal-SC language extensions have been adopted by GNU Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal Sol was designed around 1983 by a French team to implement a Unix-like system named Sol.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It was standard Pascal level-1 (with parameterized array bounds) but the definition allowed alternative keywords and predefined identifiers in French and the language included a few extensions to ease system programming (e.g. an equivalent to lseek).
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The Sol team later on moved to the ChorusOS project to design a distributed operating system.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] IP Pascal is an implementation of the Pascal programming language using Micropolis DOS, but was moved rapidly to CP/M-80 running on the Z80.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It was moved to the 80386 machine types in 1994, and exists today as Windows XP and Linux implementations.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] In 2008, the system was brought up to a new level and the resulting language termed "Pascaline" (after Pascal's calculator).
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It includes objects, namespace controls, dynamic arrays, and many other extensions, and generally features the same functionality and type protection as C#.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It is the only such implementation that is also compatible with the original Pascal implementation, which is standardized as ISO 7185.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal, in its original form, is a purely procedural language and includes the traditional array of ALGOL-like control structures with reserved words such as `if`, `then`, `else`, `while`, `for`, and `case`, ranging on a single statement or a `begin`-`end` statements block.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal also has data structuring constructs not included in the original ALGOL 60 types, like records, variants, pointers, enumerations, and sets and procedure pointers.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Such constructs were in part inherited or inspired from Simula 67, ALGOL 68, Niklaus Wirth's own ALGOL W and suggestions by C.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal programs start with the `program` keyword with a list of external file descriptors as parameters (not required in Turbo Pascal etc.); then follows the main block bracketed by the `begin` and `end` keywords.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Semicolons separate statements, and the full stop (i.e., a period) ends the whole program (or *unit*).
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Letter case is ignored in Pascal source.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] A type declaration in Pascal is used to define a range of values which a variable of that type is capable of storing.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It also defines a set of operations that are permissible to be performed on variables of that type.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The range of values allowed for the basic types (except Boolean) is implementation defined.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Functions are provided for some data conversions.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] For conversion of `real` to `integer`, the following functions are available: `round` (using rounding half away from zero) and `trunc` (rounds towards zero).
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Often-used types like byte and string are already defined in many implementations.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Normally the system will use a word to store the data.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] For instance, the `byte` type may be stored in a machine integer—32 bits perhaps—rather than an 8-bit value.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal does not contain language elements that allow the basic storage types to be defined more granularly.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This capability was included in a number of Pascal extensions and follow-on languages, while others, like Modula-2, expanded the built-in set to cover most machine data types like 16-bit integers.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The `packed` keyword tells the compiler to use the most efficient method of storage for the structured data types: sets, arrays and records, rather than using one word for each element.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Packing may slow access on machines that do not offer easy access to parts of a word.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] A set is a fundamental concept for modern mathematics, and they may be used in many algorithms.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Such a feature is useful and may be faster than an equivalent construct in a language that does not support sets.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] For these examples, which involve sets over small domains, the improved performance is usually achieved by the compiler representing set variables as bit vectors.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The set operators can then be implemented efficiently as bitwise machine code operations.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] A record is a structure comprising any number of member elements called fields.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Fields are defined by specifying an identifier–data type pair delimited by a colon; nested records are possible.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The field list is then terminated by the `end` keyword.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] A record variable's fields can later be accessed by inserting a dot (`.`) between the record name and the field identifiers.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] A record may also consist of *variants*, which are constants defined by a parenthesized list of field declarations.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] A `case ... of` clause is used at the end of the record to declare the *variable part*, containing the number of variants of the type specified within the clause.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Variant records allow several fields of the record to overlap each other to save memory.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] As shown in the example above, Pascal files are sequences of components.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Every file has a buffer variable which is denoted by *f^*.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The procedures *get* (for reading) and *put* (for writing) move the buffer variable to the next element.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Read is introduced such that *read(f, x)* is the same as *x := f^; get(f);*.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Write is introduced such that *write(f, x)* is the same as *f^ := x; put(f);* The type `text` is predefined as file of char.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Here the variable *NodePtr* is a pointer to the data type *Node*, a record.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pointers to not-yet-defined types can be declared (in the above example, pNode is a pointer to a Node, but Node is not yet defined when the pointer type is defined).
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This is a forward declaration, an exception to the rule that things must be declared before they are used.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Inside of the scope of the *with* statement, a and b refer to the subfields of the record pointer *NodePtr* and not to the record Node or the pointer type pNode.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Linked lists, stacks and queues can be created by including a pointer type field (c) in the record.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Unlike many languages that feature pointers, Pascal only allows pointers to reference dynamically created variables that are anonymous, and does not allow them to reference standard static or local variables.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pointers also must have an associated type, and a pointer to one type is not compatible with a pointer to another type (e.g. a pointer to a char is not compatible with a pointer to an integer).
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This helps eliminate the type security issues inherent with other pointer implementations, particularly those used for PL/I or C.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Some of these restrictions can be lifted in newer dialects.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal is a structured programming language, meaning that the flow of control is structured into standard statements, usually without "goto" commands.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal structures programs into procedures and functions.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Generally, a procedure is used for its side effects, whereas a function is used for its return value.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Procedures and functions can be nested to any depth, and the "program" construct is the logical outermost block.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] By default, parameters are passed by value.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] If "var" precedes a parameter's name, it is passed by reference.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Each procedure or function can have its own declarations of goto labels, constants, types, variables, and other procedures and functions, which must all be in that order.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This ordering requirement was originally intended to allow efficient single-pass compilation.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] However, in some dialects (such as Delphi) the strict ordering requirement of declaration sections has been relaxed.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal adopted many language syntax features from the ALGOL language, including the use of a semicolon as a statement separator.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This is in contrast to other languages, such as PL/I and C, which use the semicolon as a statement terminator.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] No semicolon is needed before the `end` keyword of a record type declaration, a block, or a *case* statement; before the `until` keyword of a repeat statement; and before the `else` keyword of an *if* statement.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The presence of an extra semicolon was not permitted in early versions of Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] However, the addition of ALGOL-like empty statements in the 1973 *Revised Report* and later changes to the language in ISO 7185:1983 now allow for optional semicolons in most of these cases.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] A semicolon is still not permitted immediately before the `else` keyword in an *if* statement, because the `else` follows a single statement, not a statement sequence.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] In nested ifs, a semicolon cannot be used to avoid the dangling else problem (where the inner if does not have an else, but the outer if does) by putatively terminating the nested if with a semicolon – this instead terminates both if clauses.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Instead, an explicit `begin`...`end` block must be used.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] In 1983, the language was standardized in the international standard IEC/ISO 7185 and several local country-specific standards, including the American ANSI/IEEE770X3.97-1983, and ISO 7185:1983.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] These two standards differed only in that the ISO standard included a "level 1" extension for conformant arrays (an array where the boundaries of the array are not known until run time), where ANSI did not allow for this extension to the original (Wirth version) language.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] In 1989, ISO 7185 was revised (ISO 7185:1990) to correct various errors and ambiguities found in the original document.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The ISO 7185 was stated to be a clarification of Wirth's 1974 language as detailed by the User Manual and Report [Jensen and Wirth], but was also notable for adding "Conformant Array Parameters" as a level 1 to the standard, level 0 being Pascal without conformant arrays.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This addition was made at the request of C.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Hoare, and with the approval of Niklaus Wirth.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The precipitating cause was that Hoare wanted to create a Pascal version of the (NAG) Numerical Algorithms Library, which had originally been written in FORTRAN, and found that it was not possible to do so without an extension that would allow array parameters of varying size.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Similar considerations motivated the inclusion in ISO 7185 of the facility to specify the parameter types of procedural and functional parameters.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Niklaus Wirth himself referred to the 1974 language as "the Standard", for example, to differentiate it from the machine specific features of the CDC 6000 compiler.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This language was documented in *The Pascal Report*, the second part of the "Pascal users manual and report".
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] On the large machines (mainframes and minicomputers) Pascal originated on, the standards were generally followed.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] On IBM PCs, the Borland standards Turbo Pascal and Delphi have the greatest number of users.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Thus, it is typically important to understand whether a particular implementation corresponds to the original Pascal language, or a Borland dialect of it.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The IBM PC versions of the language began to differ with the advent of UCSD Pascal, an interpreted implementation that featured several extensions to the language, along with several omissions and changes.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Many UCSD language features survive today, including in Borland's dialect.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] In 1990, an extended Pascal standard was created as ISO/IEC 10206, which is identical in technical content to IEEE/ANSI 770X3.160-1989 As of 2019, support of Extended Pascal in FreePascal Compiler is planned.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The key feature of Extended Pascal is Modularity and Separate Compilation.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Extended Pascal Application source code files can be separated into one "program file" and multiple "module files".
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Each module file has their own type, constant, variable and procedure/function definitions and programmers can change the order of these "entity definition" areas.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Also, there are some module-specific definition areas called "initialization" areas with the statement `to begin do ...` and "finalization" areas with the statement `to end do ...`, which can manage the initial state and memory allocation of entities inside the module.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] By inserting `import ...` statements between module/program declaration and definition areas, modules can share their own entities with other modules (and programs).
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Other major features include variable binding, collections of similar types (Schemata), comprehensive string facilities, complex number type support, `otherwise` keyword for default branch flow in `case` statement, and short circuit boolean evaluation.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Niklaus Wirth's Zürich version of Pascal was issued outside ETH in two basic forms: the CDC 6000 compiler source, and a porting kit called Pascal-P system.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The Pascal-P compiler left out several features of the full language that were not required to bootstrap the compiler.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] For example, procedures and functions used as parameters, undiscriminated variant records, packing, dispose, interprocedural gotos and other features of the full compiler were omitted.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] UCSD Pascal, under Professor Kenneth Bowles, was based on the Pascal-P2 kit, and consequently shared several of the Pascal-P language restrictions.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] UCSD Pascal was later adopted as Apple Pascal, and continued through several versions there.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Although UCSD Pascal expanded the subset Pascal in the Pascal-P kit by adding back standard Pascal constructs, it was still not a complete standard installation of Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] In the early 1990s, Alan Burns and Geoff Davies developed Pascal-FC, an extension to Pl/0 (from Niklaus' book *Algorithms + Data Structures = Programs*).
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Several constructs were added to use Pascal-FC as a teaching tool for Concurrent Programming (such as semaphores, monitors, channels, remote-invocation and resources).
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] To be able to demonstrate concurrency, the compiler output (a kind of P-code) could then be executed on a virtual machine.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This virtual machine not only simulated a normal – fair – environment, but could also simulate extreme conditions (unfair mode).
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Borland's Turbo Pascal, written by Anders Hejlsberg, was written in assembly language independent of UCSD and the Zürich compilers.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] However, it adopted much of the same subset and extensions as the UCSD compiler.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This is probably because the UCSD system was the most common Pascal system suitable for developing applications on the resource-limited microprocessor systems available at that time.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Pascal generated a wide variety of responses in the computing community, both critical and complimentary.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Wirth's initial definition of the language was widely criticized.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] In particular, Nico Habermann commented in his "Critical Comments on the Programming Language Pascal" (1973) that many of its constructs were poorly defined, in particular for data types, ranges, structures, and goto.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Later, Brian Kernighan, who popularized the C language, outlined his criticisms of Pascal in 1981 in his article "Why Pascal is Not My Favorite Programming Language".
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] The most serious problem Kernighan described was that array sizes and string lengths were part of the type, so it was not possible to write a function that would accept variable-length arrays or even strings as parameters.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] This made it unfeasible to write, for example, a sorting library.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Kernighan also criticized the unpredictable order of evaluation of Boolean expressions, poor library support, and lack of static variables, and raised a number of smaller issues.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Also, he stated that the language did not provide any simple constructs to "escape" (knowingly and forcibly ignore) restrictions and limitations.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Another difficulty was that, like ALGOL 60, the language did not allow procedures or functions passed as parameters to predefine the expected type of their parameters.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] In the two decades after 1975, Pascal gained increasing attention and became a major programming language for important platforms (including Apple II, Apple III, Apple Lisa, Commodore systems, Z-80-based machines and IBM PC) due to the availability of UCSD Pascal and Turbo Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Despite initial criticisms, Pascal continued to evolve, and most of Kernighan's points do not apply to versions of the language which were enhanced to be suitable for commercial product development, such as Borland's Turbo Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] As Kernighan predicted in his article, most of the extensions to fix these issues were incompatible from compiler to compiler.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Since the early 1990s, however, most of the varieties seem condensed into two categories: ISO and Borland-like.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Extended Pascal addresses many of these early criticisms.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] It supports variable-length strings, variable initialization, separate compilation, short-circuit Boolean operators, and default (`otherwise`) clauses for case statements.
[src:object-pascal/pascal-programming-language] Some of the problems arising from the differences in the implementations of Pascal were later partly solved by the advent of Free Pascal, which supports several dialects with mode directives.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] For versions 6 and 7 (the last two versions), both a lower-priced Turbo Pascal and more expensive **Borland Pascal** were produced; Borland Pascal was oriented more toward professional software development, with more libraries and standard library source code.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The name Borland Pascal is also used more generically for Borland's dialect of the language Pascal, significantly different from Standard Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Borland has released three old versions of Turbo Pascal free of charge because of their historical interest: the original Turbo Pascal (now known as 1.0), and versions 3.02 and 5.5 for DOS, while Borland's French office released version 7.01 on its FTP.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Philippe Kahn first saw an opportunity for Borland, his newly formed software company, in the field of programming tools.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Historically, the vast majority of programmers saw their workflow in terms of the edit/compile/link cycle, with separate tools dedicated to each task.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Programmers wrote source code using a text editor; the source code was then compiled into object code (often requiring multiple passes), and a linker combined object code with runtime libraries to produce an executable program.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] In the early IBM PC market (1981–1983) the major programming tool vendors all made compilers that worked in a similar fashion.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] For example, the Microsoft Pascal system consisted of two compiler passes and a final linking pass (which could take minutes on systems with only floppy disks for secondary storage, even though programs were very much smaller than they are today).
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] This process was less resource-intensive than the later integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Vendors of software development tools aimed their products at professional developers, and the price for these basic tools plus ancillary tools like profilers ran into the hundreds of dollars.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The program was sold by direct mail order for US$49.95, without going through established sales channels (retailers or resellers).
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The Turbo Pascal compiler was based on the Blue Label Pascal compiler originally produced for the NasSys cassette-based operating system of the Nascom microcomputer in 1981 by Anders Hejlsberg.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Borland licensed Hejlsberg's "PolyPascal" compiler core (*Poly Data* was the name of Hejlsberg's company in Denmark), and added the user interface and editor.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Anders Hejlsberg joined the company as an employee and was the architect for all versions of the Turbo Pascal compiler and the first three versions of Borland Delphi.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] On its launch in the United States market, Turbo Pascal retailed for US$49.99, a very low price for a compiler at the time.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The integrated Pascal compiler was of good quality compared to other Pascal products of the time.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The Turbo name alluded to the speed of compiling and of the executables produced.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The edit/compile/run cycle was fast compared to other Pascal implementations because everything related to building the program was stored in RAM, and because it was a one-pass compiler written in assembly language.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Compiling was much faster than compilers for other languages (even Borland's own later compilers for C), and other Pascal compilers, and programmer time was also saved since the program could be compiled and run from the IDE.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The execution speed of these COM-format programs was a revelation for developers whose only prior experience programming microcomputers was with interpreted BASIC or UCSD Pascal, which compiled to p-code which was then interpreted at runtime.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Unlike some other development tools, Turbo Pascal disks had no copy protection.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Borland sold about 250,000 copies of Turbo Pascal in two years, which Bruce F.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Webster of *Byte* described as "an amazing figure for a computer language".
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] He reported six months later that the figure had risen to "more than 400,000 copies in a marketplace that had been estimated as having only 30,000 potential buyers".
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Jerry Pournelle wrote in the magazine in February 1984 that Turbo Pascal "comes close to what I think the computer industry is headed for: well documented, standard, plenty of good features, and a reasonable price".
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] He disliked the requirement to buy another license to distribute binaries, but noted that "it turns out not to be a lot more.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Borland only wants another $100" atop the $49.95 base price, and that "my first impression of Turbo is that it's probably worth $149.95.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] It looks to do everything MT+ *with the Speed Programming Package* does, and maybe even do it faster and better".
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Pournelle reported in July that Turbo 2.0's overlays "[allow] you to write big programs".
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] According to Kahn, IBM had refused to resell Turbo Pascal unless the price was at least $200; Pournelle noted that "Turbo is much better than the Pascal IBM sells", and unlike the latter was compatible with the IBM PCjr.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Three *Byte* reviewers praised Turbo Pascal in the same issue.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] One reviewer said that because of dialect differences "Turbo is not really Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] While cautioning that it was not suitable for developing very large applications, he concluded that Turbo Pascal "is well written, fun to use at times, and fast enough to make up for its few shortcomings ... it is a bargain that shouldn't be passed up".
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] A second called the DOS version "without doubt, the best software value I have ever purchased", while a third said that Borland "deserves praise for" the "high-value" CP/M version.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Also in July 1984, *Creative Computing* favorably compared Turbo Pascal to what the reviewer described as mediocre and expensive Pascals from UCSD, IBM, and Microsoft.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] He reported converting code written in IBM Pascal in less than 30 minutes, and that "under IBM Pascal, the average program took two weeks to write.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] With Turbo Pascal, the average is now two days".
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] While noting the .COM and 64 KB limitations, the reviewer approved of Turbo's close adherence to the Jensen and Wirth language standard.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The documentation was, he wrote, of "above average readability" and superior to IBM Pascal's.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] "My only fear", the review concluded, was that "it is grossly underpriced, and I worry that people might fail to take it seriously".
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] "Turbo Pascal is the Pascal to acquire", *Computer Language* in September said of version 2.0.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Praising its speed, extensions including PC graphics and sound, documentation, ease of using overlays, and "highly standard syntax", the magazine recommended Turbo to both new and experienced programmers.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] *PC Magazine* was similarly complimentary in November, stating that "nothing like Turbo Pascal has ever existed for PC-DOS before".
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] It praised 2.0's low price, speed, stability, ease of implementing overlays, and unusually good documentation for a compiler, and noted the existence of many utilities for Turbo Pascal from other companies.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The review stated that the IDE that simplified the edit-compile-run-debug loop made Turbo Pascal accessible, like BASIC, to new programmers.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Pournelle in August 1985 called version 3.0 "a distinct improvement on the already impressive version 2" and said that the new book license "seems quite fair to me".
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] He said that "Turbo Pascal has got to be the best value in languages on the market today", and that Borland led the industry in "delivering excellent products at reasonable costs".
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Webster also praised 3.0, stating in August 1985 that Turbo Pascal "is best known for its small size, incredible compile speeds, and fast execution times".
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] He noted that the software's quality and low price was especially surprising after the "JRT Pascal fiasco", and stated that even at the new higher $69.95 price, it was "probably still the best software deal on the market".
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Despite finding what the magazine called "a serious bug" in 3.0, and decreased compatibility with PC clones, *Byte* in February 1986 stated that "it is hard to avoid recommending Turbo to anyone who wants to program in Pascal", citing improved speed and graphic routines.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] When reviewing four other Pascal compilers in December 1986, the magazine described Turbo Pascal 3.0 as "practical and attractive to programmers at all levels of expertise".
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Besides allowing applications larger than 64 KB, *Byte* in 1988 reported substantially faster compiling and executing for version 4.0, and that although it did not maintain previous versions' "almost total" backward compatibility, conversion was fast and easy.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The reviewer concluded, "I highly recommend Turbo Pascal 4.0 as an addition to any programmer's software repertoire".
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Scott MacGregor of Microsoft said that Bill Gates "couldn't understand why our stuff was so slow" compared to Turbo Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] "He would bring in poor Greg Whitten [programming director of Microsoft languages] and yell at him for half an hour" because their company was unable to defeat Kahn's small startup, MacGregor recalled.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] By 1995 Borland had dropped Turbo/Borland Pascal and replaced it with the rapid application development (RAD) environment Borland Delphi, based on Object Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The 32- and 64-bit Delphi versions still support the more portable Pascal enhancements of the earlier products (i.e., those not specific to 16-bit code) including the earlier static object model.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] This language backwards compatibility means much old Turbo Pascal code can still be compiled and run in a modern environment today.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] In 2006, Borland revived the Turbo brand name for a new line of single-language IDEs based on Borland Developer Studio 2006, including Turbo Delphi, Turbo C++, and Turbo C#.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] These products were discontinued in October 2009.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Other suppliers have produced software development tools compatible with Turbo Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The best-known are Free Pascal and Virtual Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] While all versions of Turbo Pascal could include inline machine code, starting with version 6 it was possible to integrate assembly language within Pascal source code.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Support for the various x86 memory models was provided by inline assembly, compiler options, and language extensions such as the "absolute" keyword.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The Turbo Assembler, TASM, a standard x86 assembler independent of TP, and source-compatible with the widely used Microsoft Macro Assembler MASM, was supplied with the enhanced "Borland Pascal" versions.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The IDE provided several debugging facilities, including single stepping, examination and changing of variables, and conditional breakpoints.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] In later versions assembly-language blocks could be stepped through.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The user could add breakpoints on variables and registers in an IDE window.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Programs using IBM PC graphics mode could flip between graphics and text mode automatically or manually, or display both on two screens.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] For cases where the relatively simple debugging facilities of the IDE were insufficient, Turbopower Software produced a more powerful debugger, T-Debug.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The same company produced Turbo Analyst and Overlay Manager for Turbo Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] T-Debug was later updated for Turbo Pascal 4, but discontinued with the release of Borland's Turbo Debugger (TD), which also allowed some hardware intervention on computers equipped with the new 80386 processor.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] TD was usually supplied in conjunction with the Turbo Assembler and the Turbo Profiler, a code profiler that reported on the time spent in each part of the program to assist program optimisation by finding bottlenecks.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The books included with Borland Pascal had detailed descriptions of the Intel assembler language, including the number of clock cycles required by each instruction.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Development and debugging could be carried out entirely within the IDE unless the advanced debugging facilities of Turbopower T-Debug, and later TD, were required.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Later versions also supported remote debugging via an RS-232 communication cable.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Over the years, Borland enhanced not only the IDE, but also extended the programming language.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] A development system based on ISO standard Pascal requires implementation-specific extensions for the development of real-world applications on the platforms they target.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Standard Pascal is designed to be platform-independent, so prescribes no low-level access to hardware- or operating system-dependent facilities.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Standard Pascal also does not prescribe how a large program should be split into separate compiling units.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] From version 4, Turbo Pascal adopted the concept of *units* from UCSD Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Units were used as external function libraries, like the object files used in other languages such as FORTRAN or C.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] For example, the line `uses crt;` in a program included the unit called crt; the `uses` is the mechanism for using other compiling units.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] `interface` and `implementation` were the keywords used to specify, within the unit, what was (and what was not) visible outside the unit.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] This is similar to the `public` and `private` keywords in other languages such as C++ and Java.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Units in Borland's Pascal were similar to Modula-2's separate compiling system.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] In 1987, when Turbo Pascal 4 was released, Modula-2 was making inroads as an educational language which could replace Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Borland, in fact, had a Turbo Modula-2 compiler, but only released it on CP/M (its user interface was almost identical to that of Turbo Pascal 1–3) with little marketing.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] A much improved DOS version was developed, but as Borland was unwilling to publish the results, the authors including Niels Jensen bought the rights and formed Jensen & Partners International to publish it as JPI TopSpeed Modula-2.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Instead Borland chose to implement separate compiling in their established Pascal product.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Separate compiling was not part of the standard Pascal language, but was already available in UCSD Pascal, which was very popular on 8-bit machines.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Turbo Pascal syntax for units appears to have been borrowed from UCSD Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Earlier versions of Turbo Pascal, designed for computers with limited resources, supported a "chain and execute" system of dynamic linking for separately compiled objects, similar to the system widely used in BASIC.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Also, the language had a statement to include separate source code in a program when necessary, and overlaying was supported from TP3, but, as with overlays, chained objects had to fit into the original (limited) program memory space.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] As computing and storage facilities advanced, the ability to generate large EXE files was added to Turbo Pascal, with the ability to statically link and collectively load separately compiled objects.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The .TPU files output by compiling a Turbo Pascal unit are tightly linked to the internal structures of the compiler, rather than standard .OBJ linkable files.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] This improved compiling and linking times, but meant that .TPU files could not be linked with the output of other languages or even used with different releases of Turbo Pascal unless recompiled from source.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] From version 5.5 some object-oriented programming features were introduced: classes, inheritance, constructors and destructors.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The IDE was already augmented with an object browser interface showing relations between objects and methods and allowing programmers to navigate the modules easily.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Borland called its language *Object Pascal*, which was greatly extended to become the language underlying Delphi (which has two separate OOP systems).
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The name "Object Pascal" originated with the Pascal extensions developed by Apple Computer to program its Lisa and Macintosh computers.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Pascal originator Niklaus Wirth consulted in developing these extensions, which built upon the record type already present in Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Several versions of Turbo Pascal, including the last version 7, include a unit named CRT, which was used by many fullscreen text-mode applications on a CRT.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] This unit contains code in its initialization section to determine the CPU speed and calibrate delay loops.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] This code fails on processors with a speed greater than about 200 MHz and aborts immediately with a "Runtime Error 200" message.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] (the error code 200 had nothing to do with the CPU speed 200 MHz).
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] This is caused because a loop runs to count the number of times it can iterate in a fixed time, as measured by the real-time clock.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] When Turbo Pascal was developed it ran on machines with CPUs running at 2.5 to 8 MHz, and little thought was given to the possibility of vastly higher speeds, so from about 200 MHz enough iterations can be run to overflow the 16-bit counter.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] A patch was produced when machines became too fast for the original method, but failed as processor speeds increased yet further, and was superseded by others.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] There are also patches to the TP7 compiler, thus if the Pascal source is available, a new compiling's code will work without the compiled code needing a patch.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] If the source code is available, porting to libraries without CPU clock speed dependency is a solution too.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] There were several floating-point types, including `single` (the 4-byte [IEEE 754] representation) `double` (the 8-byte IEEE 754 representation), `extended` (a 10-byte IEEE 754 representation used mostly internally by numeric coprocessors) and `Real` (a 6-byte representation).
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] In the early days, `Real` was the most popular.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Most PCs of the era did not have a floating-point coprocessor so all floating-point arithmetic had to be done in software.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Borland's own floating-point algorithms on `Real` were quicker than using the other types, though its library also emulated the other types in software.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Version 1, released on 20 November 1983, was a basic all-in-one system, working in memory and producing .COM executable files for DOS and CP/M, and equivalent .CMD executables for CP/M-86 (different from .CMD batch files later used in 32-bit Microsoft Windows).
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Source code files were limited to 64 KB to simplify the IDE, and DOS .COM files were limited to 64 KB each of code, stack and global (static) variables.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Program source code could be extended by using the include facility if the source code exceeded the memory limit of the editor.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] There were different versions of Turbo Pascal for computers running DOS, CP/M, or CP/M-86 with 64 KB of memory and at least one floppy disk drive.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The CP/M version could run on the many CP/M machines of the time with Z80 processors, or an Apple II with Z80 card.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The DOS and CP/M-86 versions ran on the many 8086 and 8088 machines which became available, including the IBM PC.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The installer, lister, and compiler with its IDE, and the source code for a simple spreadsheet program called MicroCalc written by Philippe Kahn as a demonstration, would fit on a single floppy disc.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The architecture of the various machines running MS-DOS additionally limited the maximum user memory to under 1 MB (e.g., machines hardware-compatible with the IBM PC were limited to 640 KB).
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The Turbo Pascal IDE was advanced for its day.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] It was able to perform well and compile quickly with the amount of RAM on a typical home computer.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The IDE was simple and intuitive to use, and had a well-organized system of menus.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Early versions of the editor used WordStar key functions, which was the de facto standard at the time.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Later versions of the IDE, designed for PCs with more disk space and memory, could display the definitions of the keywords of the language by putting the cursor over a keyword and pressing the F1 key (conventionally used to display help).
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] In addition to standard executable programs, the compiler could generate terminate-and-stay-resident (TSR) programs, small utilities that stayed in memory and let the computer do other tasks—running several programs at the same time, multitasking, was not otherwise available.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Borland produced a small application suite called Sidekick that was a TSR letting the user keep a diary, notes, and so forth.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Additions included an overlay system, where separate overlay procedures would be automatically swapped from disk into a reserved space in memory.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] This memory was part of the 64kB RAM used by the program's code, and was automatically the size of the largest overlay procedure.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Overlay procedures could include overlay sections themselves, but unless a RAM disk was used, the resulting disk swapping could be slow.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] 2.0 also added the Dispose procedure to manage the heap, allowing individual dynamic variables to be freed, as an alternative to the more primitive 'Mark/Release' system and increased compatibility with WordStar commands plus use of the numeric keypad on the IBM PC and compatibles.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Such PCs also had new text window and CGA graphics mode commands as well as being able to use the PC's speaker for tones.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Finally, DOS and CP/M-86 machines with an 8087 maths coprocessor (or later compatible) had an alternative TURBO-87 compiler available to purchase.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] It supported the 8087's *long real* data types with a range of 1.67E-307 to 1.67E+308 to 14 significant figure precision but with a much greater processing speed.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Version 2 for CP/M-80 only runs on Z80-based CP/M machines.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Version 3 was released on 17 September 1986.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Turbo Pascal 3 supported turtle graphics.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] In addition to the default software real numbers and 8087 edition of the compiler, Borland also offered a binary-coded decimal (BCD) version (TURBOBCD) which offered the same numeric range as real data types but to 18 significant figures.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Released on 20 November 1987, Version 4 was a total rewrite, with both look and feel and internal operation much changed.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The compiler generated executables in .EXE format under DOS, rather than the simpler but more restricted .COM executables.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The by-then obsolete CP/M and CP/M-86 operating system versions were dropped when Turbo Pascal was rewritten.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Version 4 introduced units, and a full-screen text user interface with pull-down menus; earlier versions had a text-based menu screen and a separate full-screen editor.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] (Microsoft Windows was still very experimental when the first version was released, and even mice were rare.) An add-on package, the Turbo Pascal Graphix Toolbox, was available for Turbo Pascal V4.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Colour displays were replacing monochrome; Turbo Pascal version 5.0, released 24 August 1988, introduced blue as the editor's default background color, used by Borland's DOS compilers until the end of this product line in the mid-1990s.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] It also added debugger support for breakpoints and watches.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] This version, released on 2 May 1989, introduced object-oriented programming features for the Pascal language, including concept of classes, static and dynamic objects, constructors and destructors and inheritance, which would become the basis for the Object Pascal found in Borland Delphi.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The IDE uses the default blue colour scheme that would also be used on later Borland Turbo products.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Other changes to IDE include the addition of context-sensitive help with description of all built-in functions, and the ability to copy code fragments from the help to edit window.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Version 6 was released on 23 October 1990.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Changes from 5.5 include: the addition of inline assembly, the addition of the Turbo Vision library, mouse support, clipboard for text manipulations, multiple document interface supporting up to nine edit windows.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Version 7 was released on 27 October 1992.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Changes from 6.0 include support for the creation of DOS and Windows executables and Windows DLLs, and syntax highlighting.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] For version 7 Borland released a professional version of Turbo Pascal, named Borland Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Two versions named "Turbo Pascal for Windows" (TPW), for Windows 3.x, were released: TPW 1.0, based on Turbo Pascal 6 but released about 2 years later, and 1.5, released after Turbo Pascal 7; they were succeeded by Borland Pascal 7, which had Windows support.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The Windows compiler in Pascal 7 was titled *Borland Pascal for Windows*.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Both versions built Windows-compatible programs, and featured a Windows-based IDE, as opposed to the DOS-based IDE in Turbo Pascal.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The IDE and editor commands conformed to the Microsoft Windows user interface guidelines instead of the classic TP user interface.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] The support for Windows programs required the Object Windows Library (OWL), similar but not identical to that for the first release of Borland C++, and radically different from the earlier DOS Turbo Vision environment.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Turbo Pascal was superseded for the Windows platform by Delphi; the Delphi compiler can produce console programs and graphical user interface (GUI) applications, so that using Turbo and Borland Pascal became unnecessary.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Borland released *Turbo Pascal for Macintosh* in 1986.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Much like versions 1 to 3 for other operating systems, it was written in compact assembly language and had a very powerful IDE, but no good debugger.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Borland did not support this product very well, although they issued a version 1.1, patched to run on the 32-bit Macintosh II.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Macintosh support was dropped soon after.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Borland released several versions of Turbo Pascal as freeware after they became "antique software", with 1.0 for DOS on 1 February 2000, 3.02 on 10 February 2000, 5.5 on 21 February 2002, Turbo Pascal 7.01 French version in year 2000.
[src:object-pascal/turbo-pascal] Most of the downloads are still available on the successor website of Embarcadero Technologies.
[src:object-pascal/wiki-freepascal-org] The goal of this Wiki is to collect and store the knowledge necessary for the productive use of Free Pascal, Lazarus and related projects.
[src:object-pascal/wiki-freepascal-org] The Wiki is intended to be the first port of call for users looking for information on how to use the tools provided by those projects.
[src:object-pascal/wiki-freepascal-org] The Free Pascal Compiler already has user documentation available in several formats.
[src:object-pascal/wiki-freepascal-org] FPC developer information, and subjects not yet properly documented, is stored in this Wiki.
[src:object-pascal/wiki-freepascal-org] Lazarus has some gaps in its user documentation and so this Wiki is a place where anyone can edit, improve and expand the Lazarus documentation.
[src:object-pascal/wiki-freepascal-org] A Sand Box is available for new Wiki users to practise in before editing real content.
[src:object-pascal/wiki-freepascal-org] If you have any Wiki-related problems, leave a note or suggestion on the Site Feedback page or make a post in this Forum.
[src:object-pascal/wiki-freepascal-org] Wiki Portals have been created for a selection of the platforms and topics that Free Pascal and Lazarus support.
[src:object-pascal/wiki-freepascal-org] The Portals gather together all the related information for the particular platform or topic in one place to make it easier to locate.
[src:object-pascal/wiki-freepascal-org] The full list of supported platforms may be found here.
[src:object-pascal/wiki-freepascal-org] A summary of recent news stories about Free Pascal and Lazarus can be found here.
[src:object-pascal/wiki-freepascal-org] Details and screenshots of an extensive number of applications created with Free Pascal and Lazarus may be found here.
[src:object-pascal/wiki-freepascal-org] There is also plenty of source code that can be found here.
[src:object-pascal/wiki-freepascal-org] The Lazarus Bug Tracker and the Free Pascal Bug Tracker are the places to go to check if the anomaly you have encountered has already been recorded as a Free Pascal Compiler or Lazarus IDE bug and, if not, you can lodge a bug report (see How do I create a bug report) so that it can be fixed.
[src:object-pascal/wiki-freepascal-org] Even better, lodge a patch if you can (see Creating A Patch) with the bug report.
